<!-- Note: The following pages were redirects to [[Kisumimi]] before draftification: *[[Draft:Kisumimi]] *[[Kisumimi-no-Mikoto]] --> {{More citations needed|date=October 2021|talk=Untranslated refs in the reflist}}
{{Cleanup_section|reason=1) The header text is self-contradictory: ''"He appears in the ... Kojiki"'' and also ''"his name is not mentioned in the Kojiki ... There is also no mention of his achievements in the Kojiki"''. 2) Bad names: there is no "Kisumi Mimei" anywhere in Japanese sources. This is a misrepresentation of the name. 3) Bad references: the "Dictionary of Japanese Gods and Buddha", the "Japanese God Reading Dictionary", and the "Dictionary of Japanese Gods and Buddha" are all non-existant sources.|date=February 2023}} '''Kisumimi-no-mikoto'''<ref name=":0">"Ancient Japanese Encyclopedia" p341 "Kisumi no Mikoto (Kisumi Mimei)"</ref> is a character in [[Japanese mythology]], a male deity and the son of the first Emperor [[Emperor Jimmu|Jimmu]].<ref name=":1">"Dictionary of Japanese Gods and Buddha" p400 "Kisumi no Mikoto [Kisumi Mimei]"</ref><ref name=":2">"Japanese God Reading Dictionary" p118 "Kisumi Mimei"</ref> He appears in the middle volume of [[Kojiki]], but not in [[Nihon Shoki]].<ref name=":1">"Dictionary of Japanese Gods and Buddha" p400 "Kisumi no Mikoto [Kisumi Mimei]"</ref>. He is the younger brother of [[Tagishimimi]] and some speculate they were the same person.<ref name=":5" />
There is also no mention of his achievements in the Kojiki, and no mention of his descendants.
== References in Chronicles == In the "Record of Jimmu" in the middle volume of the "Kojiki," there is a sentence as follows.<ref name=":0">"Ancient Japanese Encyclopedia" p341 "Kisumi no Mikoto (Kisumi Mimei)"</ref><ref name=":1">"Dictionary of Japanese Gods and Buddha" p400 "Kisumi no Mikoto [Kisumi Mimei]"</ref> {| style="background-color:WhiteSmoke;padding: 10px;" |Therefore, when sitting in the sun, he took to wife the sister of Ata-no-Koji-kun, the son of Abirahime, [[Tagishimimi|Tagishimimi-no-Mikoto]], and the next, '''Kisumimi-no-Mikoto''', the two pillars. |-. |When [[Emperor Jimmu]] was in Hyuga, he married the sister of Ata's second son, Abira-hime, and they had two sons, [[Tagishimimi|Tagishimimi-no-Mikoto]] and Kisumimi-no-Mikoto.<ref name=":0">"Ancient Japanese Encyclopedia" p341 "Kisumi no Mikoto (Kisumi Mimei)"</ref><ref>"Japanese God Name Dictionary" p151 "Kismimi Kisumimi"</ref> |} On the other hand, in "The Chronicles of Emperor Jimmu," vol. 3 of the Nihon Shoki, there is a sentence that is largely the same as the following. However, in this text, only the name of the child is given as "Tagishimi," and there is no mention of the person who corresponds to Gisumi-no-mikoto.<ref name=":1">"Dictionary of Japanese Gods and Buddha" p400 "Kisumi no Mikoto [Kisumi Mimei]"</ref> {| style="background-color:WhiteSmoke;padding: 10px;" |The Emperor Jinmu took to wife Ahiratsuhime of Ata-eup in Hyuga Province. （Emperor Jinmu took to wife Ahiratsuhime of Ata-eup in Hyuga Province, and Tagishimimino-no-Mikoto was born.<ref name=":3">"Illustrated Emperor Jimmu" p37-41 "Emperor Jimmu"</ref> |-This is the first time I've seen it. |- ([[Emperor Jimmu]]) took to wife Ahiratsuhime of Ata-eup in the Land of Hyuga, and they had [[Tagishimimi|Tegashimimino-no-mikoto]]. |} In addition to this, in [[Kujiki|Sekaiyo Kyu-jihonki]], Volume 6, "The Chronicles of the Emperors", the names "Tagishimimi-no-mikoto" and "Kenmimi-no-mikoto" appear as the two sons of Emperor Jimmu and 