{{Cleanup_section|reason=1) The header text is self-contradictory: ''"He appears in the ... Kojiki"'' and also ''"his name is not mentioned in the Kojiki ... There is also no mention of his achievements in the Kojiki"''. 2) Bad names: there is no "Kisumi Mimei" anywhere in Japanese sources. This is a misrepresentation of the name. 3) Bad references: the "Dictionary of Japanese Gods and Buddha", the "Japanese God Reading Dictionary", and the "Dictionary of Japanese Gods and Buddha" are all non-existant sources.|date=February 2023}} '''Kisumimi-no-mikoto'''<ref name=":0">『日本古代神祇事典』p341「きすみみのみこと（岐須美美命）」</ref> is a character in [[Japanese mythology]], a male deity and the son of the first Emperor [[Emperor Jimmu|Jimmu]].<ref name=":1">『日本の神仏の辞典』p400「きすみみのみこと【岐須美美命】」</ref><ref name=":2">『日本の神様読み解き事典』p118「岐須美美命」</ref> He appears in the middle volume of [[Kojiki]], but not in [[Nihon Shoki]].<ref name=":1b"> He is the younger brother of [[Tagishimimi]] and some speculate they were the same person.<ref name=":5">{{Cite web |last=日本人名大辞典+Plus |first=デジタル版 |title=岐須美美命とは |url=https://kotobank.jp/word/%E5%B2%90%E9%A0%88%E7%BE%8E%E7%BE%8E%E5%91%BD-1069200 |access-date=2022-01-12 |website=コトバンク |language=ja}}</ref>
There is also no mention of his achievements in the Kojiki, and no mention of his descendants.
== References in Chronicles == In the "Record of Jimmu" in the middle volume of the "Kojiki," there is a sentence as follows.<ref name=":0b">"Ancient Japanese Encyclopedia" p341 "Kisumi no Mikoto (Kisumi Mimei)"</ref><ref name=":1b">"Dictionary of Japanese Gods and Buddha" p400 "Kisumi no Mikoto [Kisumi Mimei]"</ref> {| style="background-color:WhiteSmoke;padding: 10px;" |Therefore, when sitting in the sun, he took to wife the sister of Ata-no-Koji-kun, the son of [[Ahiratsu-hime]], [[Tagishimimi|Tagishimimi-no-Mikoto]], and the next, '''Kisumimi-no-Mikoto''', the two pillars. |-. |When [[Emperor Jimmu]] was in Hyuga, he married the sister of Ata's second son, [[Ahiratsu-hime]], and they had two sons, [[Tagishimimi|Tagishimimi-no-Mikoto]] and Kisumimi-no-Mikoto.<ref name=":0b"/><ref>『日本神名辞典』p151「岐須美美命」</ref> |} On the other hand, in "The Chronicles of Emperor Jimmu," vol. 3 of the Nihon Shoki, there is a sentence that is largely the same as the following. However, in this text, only the name of the child is given as "Tagishimi," and there is no mention of the person who corresponds to Kisumimi-no-mikoto.<ref name=":1b"/> {| style="background-color:WhiteSmoke;padding: 10px;" |Emperor Jinmu took to wife Ahiratsuhime of Ata-eup in Hyuga Province, and Tagishimimino-no-Mikoto was born.<ref name=":3">『図説 歴代天皇紀』p37-41「神武天皇」</ref> |-This is the first time I've seen it. |- ([[Emperor Jimmu]]) took to wife Ahiratsuhime of Ata-eup in the Land of Hyuga, and they had [[Tagishimimi|Tegashimimino-no-mikoto]]. |} In addition to this, in [[Kujiki|Sekaiyo Kyu-jihonki]], Volume 6, "The Chronicles of the Emperors", the names "Tagishimimi-no-mikoto" and "Kenmimi-no-mikoto" appear as the two sons of Emperor Jimmu and Princess Ohirazu.<ref>『日本古代神祇事典』p340「きしみみのみこと（研耳命）」</ref> However, they do not appear in Volume 7, "The Chronicles of the Emperor".<ref name=":4">吉井厳「茨田連の祖先伝承と茨田堤築造の物語」（万葉71号, P1-p21,1969年） 万葉学会</ref>
