{{Cleanup_section|reason=1) The header text is self-contradictory: ''"He appears in the ... Kojiki"'' and also ''"his name is not mentioned in the Kojiki ... There is also no mention of his achievements in the Kojiki"''. 2) Bad names: there is no "Kisumi Mimei" anywhere in Japanese sources. This is a misrepresentation of the name. 3) Bad references: the "Dictionary of Japanese Gods and Buddha", the "Japanese God Reading Dictionary", and the "Dictionary of Japanese Gods and Buddha" are all non-existant sources.|date=February 2023}} '''Kisumimi-no-mikoto'''<ref name=":0">『日本古代神祇事典』p341「きすみみのみこと（岐須美美命）」</ref> is a character in [[Japanese mythology]], a male deity and the son of the first Emperor [[Emperor Jimmu|Jimmu]].<ref name=":1">『日本の神仏の辞典』p400「きすみみのみこと【岐須美美命】」</ref><ref name=":2">『日本の神様読み解き事典』p118「岐須美美命」</ref> He is the younger brother of [[Tagishimimi]] and some speculate they were the same person.<ref name=":5">{{Cite web |last=日本人名大辞典+Plus |first=デジタル版 |title=岐須美美命とは |url=https://kotobank.jp/word/%E5%B2%90%E9%A0%88%E7%BE%8E%E7%BE%8E%E5%91%BD-1069200 |access-date=2022-01-12 |website=コトバンク |language=ja}}</ref>
== References in the Kiki == The [[Nihon Shoki]] simple describes him and Tagishimimi as being born to [[Ahiratsu-hime]] and [[Emperor Jimmu]].<ref>[https://www.forgottenbooks.com/de/download/Nihongi_10851439.pdf Nihon Shoki] page 110</ref>
